# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gltf-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics, contrary to what the name suggests, are most often displayed on two-dimensional displays.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike 3D film and similar techniques, the result is two-dimensional, without visual depth.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] More often, 3D graphics are being displayed on 3D displays, like in virtual reality systems.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3D graphics stand in contrast to 2D computer graphics which typically use completely different methods and formats for creation and rendering.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics rely on many of the same algorithms as 2D computer vector graphics in the wire-frame model and 2D computer raster graphics in the final rendered display.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] In computer graphics software, 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and similarly, 3D may use some 2D rendering techniques.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] The objects in 3D computer graphics are often referred to as 3D models.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike the rendered image, a model's data is contained within a graphical data file.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] A 3D model is a mathematical representation of *any* three-dimensional object; a model is not technically a *graphic* until it is displayed.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] A model can be displayed visually as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering, or it can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] With 3D printing, models are rendered into an actual 3D physical representation of themselves, with some limitations as to how accurately the physical model can match the virtual model.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] William Fetter was credited with coining the term *computer graphics* in 1961 to describe his work at Boeing.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] An early example of interactive 3-D computer graphics was explored in 1963 by the Sketchpad program at Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] One of the first displays of computer animation was *Futureworld* (1976), which included an animation of a human face and a hand that had originally appeared in the 1972 experimental short *A Computer Animated Hand*, created by University of Utah students Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software began appearing for home computers in the late 1970s.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] The earliest known example is *3D Art Graphics*, a set of 3-D computer graphics effects, written by Kazumasa Mitazawa and released in June 1978 for the Apple II.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Virtual Reality 3D is a version of 3D computer graphics.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Although the first VR headsets appeared in the late 1950s, VR did not become widely popular until the 2000s.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] In 2012 the Oculus was released and since then, the 3D VR headset world has expanded.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] The modeling describes the process of forming the shape of an object.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] The two most common sources of 3D models are those that an artist or engineer originates on a computer with a 3D modeling tool, or models scanned into a computer from real-world objects (polygonal modeling, patch modeling, and NURBS modeling are some popular tools used in 3D modeling).
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Models can also be produced procedurally or via physical simulation.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Basically, a 3D model is formed from points called vertices that define the shape and form polygons.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] A polygon is an area formed from at least three vertices (a triangle).
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] The overall integrity of the model and its suitability to use in animation depend on the structure of the polygons.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Before rendering into an image, objects must be laid out in a 3D scene.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] This defines spatial relationships between objects, including location and size.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Animation refers to the temporal description of an object (i.e., how it moves and deforms over time).
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Popular methods include keyframing, inverse kinematics, and motion-capture).
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] These techniques are often used in combination.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] As with animation, physical simulation also specifies motion.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Stop Motion has multiple categories within such as Claymation, Cutout, Silhouette, Lego, Puppets, and Pixelation.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Claymation is the use of models made of clay used for an animation.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples are Clay Fighter and Clay Jam.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Lego animation is one of the more common types of stop motion.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Lego stop motion is the use of the figures themselves moving around.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples of this are Lego Island and Lego Harry Potter.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating light transport to get photo-realistic images, or by applying an art style as in non-photorealistic rendering.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] The two basic operations in realistic rendering are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] This step is usually performed using 3-D computer graphics software or a 3-D graphics API.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Altering the scene into a suitable form for rendering also involves 3D projection, which displays a three-dimensional image in two dimensions.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Materials and textures are properties that the render engine uses to render the model.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] One can give the model materials to tell the render engine how to treat light when it hits the surface.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Textures are used to give the material color using a color or albedo map, or give the surface features using a bump map or normal map.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] It can also be used to deform the model itself using a displacement map.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software produces computer-generated imagery (CGI) through 3D modeling and 3D rendering or produces 3-D models for analytical, scientific, entertainment, and industrial purposes.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] There are many varieties of files supporting 3-D graphics, for example, Blender (.blend), Wavefront (.obj), .fbx and .x DirectX files.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Each file type generally tends to have its own unique data structure.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Each file format can be accessed through its respective applications, such as DirectX files, and Quake.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Alternatively, files can be accessed through third-party standalone programs, or via manual decompilation.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling software is a class of 3-D computer graphics software used to produce 3-D models.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications or modelers.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling starts by describing 3 display models: drawing points, drawing lines and drawing triangles and other polygonal patches.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers allow users to create and alter models via their 3-D mesh.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Users can add, subtract, stretch and otherwise change the mesh to their desire.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be viewed from a variety of angles, usually simultaneously.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be rotated and the view can be zoomed in and out.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers can export their models to files, which can then be imported into other applications as long as the metadata are compatible.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Many modelers allow importers and exporters to be plugged-in, so they can read and write data in the native formats of other applications.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Most 3-D modelers contain a number of related features, such as ray tracers and other rendering alternatives and texture mapping facilities.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some also contain features that support or allow animation of models.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some may be able to generate full-motion video of a series of rendered scenes (i.e. animation).
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Computer-aided design software may employ the same fundamental 3-D modeling techniques that 3-D modeling software uses but their goal differs.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] They are used in computer-aided engineering, computer-aided manufacturing, Finite element analysis, product lifecycle management, 3D printing and computer-aided architectural design.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] After producing a video, studios then edit or composite the video using programs such as Adobe Premiere Pro or Final Cut Pro at the mid-level, or Autodesk Combustion, Digital Fusion, Shake at the high-end.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Match moving software is commonly used to match live video with computer-generated video, keeping the two in sync as the camera moves.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Use of real-time computer graphics engines to create a cinematic production is called machinima.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Not all computer graphics that appear 3D are based on a wireframe model.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics with 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Visual artists may also copy or visualize 3D effects and manually render photo-realistic effects without the use of filters.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Some video games use 2.5D graphics, involving restricted projections of three-dimensional environments, such as isometric graphics or virtual cameras with fixed angles, either as a way to improve performance of the game engine or for stylistic and gameplay concerns.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] By contrast, games using 3D computer graphics without such restrictions are said to use true 3D.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Cutout is the use of flat materials such as paper.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Everything is cut out of paper including the environment, characters, and even some props.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Silhouette is similar to cutouts except they are one solid color, black.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Puppets are dolls and different puppets used in the game.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] An example of this would be Yoshi's Wooly World.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] Pixelation is when the entire game appears pixelated, this includes the characters and the environment around them.
[src:gltf-format/3d-computer-graphics] One example of this is seen in Shovel Knight.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The glTF format stores data primarily in JSON.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The JSON may also contain blobs of binary data known as buffers, and refer to external files, for storing mesh data, images, etc.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The binary .glb format also contains JSON text, but serialized with binary chunk headers to allow blobs to be directly appended to the file.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The fundamental building blocks of a glTF *scene* are *nodes*.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Nodes are organized into a hierarchy, such that a node may have other nodes defined as children.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Nodes may have *transforms* relative to their parent.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Nodes may refer to *resources*, such as *meshes*, *skins*, and *cameras*.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Meshes may refer to *materials*, which refer to *textures*, which refer to *images*.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Scenes are defined using an array of root nodes.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Most of the top-level glTF properties use a flat hierarchy for storage.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Nodes are saved in an array and are referred to by index, including by other nodes.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] A glTF scene refers to its root nodes by index.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Furthermore, nodes refer to meshes by index, which refer to materials by index, which refer to textures by index, which refer to images by index.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] All glTF data structures support being extended using a JSON property, allowing arbitrary JSON data to be added.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Members of the COLLADA working group conceived the file format in 2012.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] At SIGGRAPH 2012, Khronos presented a demo of glTF, which was then called WebGL Transmissions Format (WebGL TF).
[src:gltf-format/gltf] On October 19, 2015, Khronos released the glTF 1.0 specification.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] At SIGGRAPH 2016, Oculus announced their adoption of glTF citing the similarities to their ovrscene format.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] In October 2016, Microsoft joined the 3D Formats working group at Khronos to collaborate on glTF.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The second version, glTF 2.0, was released in June 2017, and is a complete overhaul of the file format from version 1.0, with most tools adopting the 2.0 version.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Based on a proposal by Fraunhofer originally presented at SIGGRAPH 2016, physically based rendering (PBR) was added, replacing WebGL shaders used in glTF 1.0. glTF 2.0 added the GLB binary format into the base specification.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Other upgrades include sparse accessors and morph targets for techniques such as facial animation, and schema tweaks and breaking changes for corner cases or performance such as replacing top-level glTF object properties with arrays for faster index-based access.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] There is ongoing work towards import and export in Unity and an integrated multi-engine viewer and validator.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] On March 3, 2017, Microsoft announced that they would be using glTF 2.0 as the 3D asset format across their product line, including Paint 3D, 3D Viewer, Remix 3D, Babylon.js, and Microsoft Office.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Sketchfab also announced support for glTF 2.0.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The glTF and GLB formats are used on and supported by companies including DGG, UX3D, Sketchfab, Facebook, Microsoft, Meta, Google, Adobe, Box, TurboSquid, Unreal Engine, Unity, and Qt Quick 3D.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The format has been noted as an important standard for augmented reality, integrating with modeling software such as Autodesk Maya, Autodesk 3ds Max, and Poly.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] In February 2020, the Smithsonian Institution launched their Open Access Initiative, releasing approximately 2.8 million 2D images and 3D models into the public domain, using glTF for the 3D models.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] In July 2022, glTF 2.0 was released as the ISO/IEC 12113:2022 International Standard.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Khronos stated they would make regular submissions to bring updates and new widely adopted glTF functionality into refreshed versions of ISO/IEC 12113 to ensure that there is no long-term divergence between the ISO/IEC and Khronos specifications.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The open-source game engine Godot supports importing glTF 2.0 files since version 3.0 and export since version 4.0.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The glTF format can be extended with arbitrary JSON to add new data and functionality.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Extensions can be placed on any part of a glTF, including nodes, animations, materials, textures, and on the entire document.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Khronos keeps a non-comprehensive registry of glTF extensions on GitHub, including all official Khronos extensions and a few third-party extensions.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] 3D Tiles, an OGC Community Standard, builds on glTF to add a spatial data structure, metadata, and declarative styling for streaming massive heterogeneous 3D geospatial datasets.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] VRM, a model format for VR, is built on the .glb format.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] It is a 3D humanoid avatar specification and file format.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Khronos maintains the glTF Sample Viewer for viewing glTF assets.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Khronos also maintains the glTF Validator for validating if 3D models conform to the glTF specification.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Khronos maintains a glTF Compressor tool to interactively optimize and fine-tune compression settings for glTF assets using KTX 2.0 textures.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] glTF loaders are in open-source WebGL engines including PlayCanvas, Three.js, Babylon.js, Cesium, PEX, xeogl, and A-Frame.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The Godot game engine supports and recommends the glTF format, with both import and export support.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Open-source glTF converters are available from COLLADA, FBX, and OBJ.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Open-source glTF utility libraries are available for programming languages including JavaScript, Node.js, C++, C#, Python, Haskell, Java, Go, Rust, Haxe, Ada, and TypeScript.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Khronos keeps a list of these libraries and other related applications on their ecosystem site.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The Khronos 3D Commerce Working Group released Asset Creation Guidelines in 2020 outlining best practices for use of the glTF file format in 3D Commerce.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] In 2025, the Working Group launched Asset Creation Guidelines 2.0, a continuously updated resource with additional guidance for geometry, mesh optimization, UV maps, textures, materials/PBR performance, and web optimization.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] The Khronos PBR Neutral Tone Mappers specification is a tone mapper designed to faithfully reproduce an object's base color, hue, and saturation when using PBR rendering under grayscale lighting, supporting brand- and product-accurate color representation.
[src:gltf-format/gltf] Khronos maintains the glTF Asset Auditor to allow retailers and advertising technology platforms to validate 3D assets against either a default Audit Profile modelled on the 2020 3D Commerce Asset Creation Guidelines or a custom profile defined by the target application.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] The Khronos Group was founded in 2000 by companies including 3Dlabs, ATI, Discreet, Evans & Sutherland, Intel, SGI, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] Promoter members include AMD, Apple, Arm, Epic Games, Google, Huawei, Nokia, Imagination, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung, Sony, Valve and Verisilicon.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] Each specification / standard is managed by a working group which is established to define the requirements, solicit input, discuss, and create a specification.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] A timeline of API Specification ratification and releases can be found on the Khronos Group website.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] Typically, Khronos first creates an exploratory group to gauge industry interest before creating a working group, which companies can join as members to assist in the development of the standard.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] Khronos members may contribute to the development of Khronos API specifications, vote at various stages before public deployment, and accelerate delivery of their platforms and applications through early access to specification drafts and conformance tests.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] To ensure that the standards are consistently implemented and to create a reliable platform for developers, any product that implements a Khronos API standard must pass conformance tests.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] An API Adopter Program enables companies to test their products for conformance.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] Membership in Khronos Group provides access to an IP framework designed to protect participant IP.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] Khronos members agree not to assert IP rights against adopters implementing Khronos specifications.
[src:gltf-format/khronos-group] The IP framework protects Khronos members from exposure to patent lawsuits and reduces the amount of IP that needs to be licensed from other group members.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:gltf-format/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
